## 📖 Project Overview

Neurodegenerative disorders such as **Alzheimer's Disease (AD)** and **Frontotemporal Dementia (FTD)** cause progressive deterioration of brain function and significantly alter neural activity. Electroencephalography (EEG) provides a **non-invasive, cost-effective, and clinically valuable** approach for measuring these changes in brain activity.

This project focuses on developing an **EEG-based Brain Disease Classification System** capable of distinguishing between:

* 🧠 Alzheimer's Disease (AD)
* 🧠 Frontotemporal Dementia (FTD)
* 🧠 Cognitively Normal (CN)

The project combines **EEG signal processing**, **feature extraction**, **dimensionality reduction**, and **deep learning** techniques to build an accurate and explainable classification pipeline.

---

# 🎯 Objectives

* Load and preprocess resting-state EEG recordings
* Visualize multichannel EEG signals
* Analyze Power Spectral Density (PSD)
* Compare brain activity across subjects
* Extract meaningful EEG features
* Perform dimensionality reduction using PCA and t-SNE
* Build machine learning and deep learning models for disease classification
* Improve model interpretability using Explainable AI techniques

---

# 📂 Dataset

This project utilizes the publicly available **OpenNeuro Dataset (ds004504)**.

## Dataset Summary

| Category                      | Subjects |
| ----------------------------- | -------: |
| Alzheimer's Disease (AD)      |   **36** |
| Frontotemporal Dementia (FTD) |   **23** |
| Cognitively Normal (CN)       |   **29** |
| **Total Participants**        |   **88** |

---

# 👥 Participant Information

| Parameter       |               AD |              FTD |               CN |
| --------------- | ---------------: | ---------------: | ---------------: |
| Subjects        |               36 |               23 |               29 |
| Mean Age        | 66.4 ± 7.9 years | 63.6 ± 8.2 years | 67.9 ± 5.4 years |
| Mean MMSE Score |     17.75 ± 4.50 |     22.17 ± 8.22 |               30 |

**Disease Duration (Median):** 25 Months

The cognitive status of each participant was evaluated using the **Mini-Mental State Examination (MMSE)**.

---

# 🧠 EEG Acquisition Details

The EEG recordings were collected at the **2nd Department of Neurology, AHEPA General Hospital, Thessaloniki, Greece** using a **Nihon Kohden EEG-2100 Clinical EEG System**.

## Recording Specifications

| Parameter             | Value                       |
| --------------------- | --------------------------- |
| Recording Type        | Resting-State (Eyes Closed) |
| EEG Channels          | 19                          |
| Reference Electrodes  | A1 & A2                     |
| Electrode Placement   | International 10–20 System  |
| Sampling Frequency    | **500 Hz**                  |
| Resolution            | **10 μV/mm**                |
| High Frequency Filter | **70 Hz**                   |
| Skin Impedance        | **< 5 kΩ**                  |

### EEG Channels

```text
Fp1  Fp2
F7   F3   Fz   F4   F8
T3   C3   Cz   C4   T4
T5   P3   Pz   P4   T6
O1   O2
```

---

# 🧹 Dataset Preprocessing

The original EEG recordings were exported to **EEGLAB (.set)** format.

The dataset contains:

* Raw EEG recordings
* Preprocessed EEG recordings (`derivatives/`)

The preprocessing pipeline applied by the dataset authors includes:

1. Butterworth Bandpass Filtering (0.5–45 Hz)
2. Re-referencing to A1–A2
3. Artifact Subspace Reconstruction (ASR)
4. Independent Component Analysis (ICA)
5. Automatic artifact removal using ICLabel

These preprocessing steps reduce noise and remove artifacts such as eye movements and muscle activity.

